Certainly! Let's assume you have an XML file named "example.xml" with the following content:<Root>
    <Target>
        <Element>Existing Content</Element>
    </Target>
</Root>And you have an input file named "input.txt" with the following content:This is the new content.Now, you can use the PowerShell script to add the new content to the XML file. Save the script in a file, for example, "update-xml.ps1," and run it:# update-xml.ps1

# Load XML from a file
$xmlFilePath = "C:\Path\To\Your\example.xml"
$xmlContent = Get-Content -Path $xmlFilePath

# Create an XML object
$xml = [xml]$xmlContent

# Define XPath expression to find the target element
$xPath = "//Root/Target/Element"

# Find the element using Select-Xml
$targetElement = $xml | Select-Xml -XPath $xPath

# Check if the element exists
if ($targetElement.Node) {
    # Read content from input file
    $inputFilePath = "C:\Path\To\Your\input.txt"
    $newContent = Get-Content -Path $inputFilePath

    # Add new content or modify existing content
    $newElement = $xml.CreateElement("NewElement")
    $newElement.InnerText = $newContent

    $targetElement.Node.AppendChild($newElement)

    # Save the modified XML
    $xml.Save($xmlFilePath)

    Write-Host "Content added successfully."
} else {
    Write-Host "Target element not found."
}Run the script, and it will update the XML file. After running the script, the "example.xml" file will look like this:<Root>
    <Target>
        <Element>Existing Content<NewElement>This is the new content.</NewElement></Element>
    </Target>
</Root>Adjust the file paths in the script according to your actual file locations.
